        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"total_weeks\":16,\"goal_description\":\"Return From Injury — Plantar Fasciitis Recovery & Base Rebuild\",\"phases\":[{\"phase_type\":\"Base\",\"weeks\":4,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":8,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":12,\"intensity_distribution\":\"100% easy, walk breaks as needed\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"Recovery\",\"CrossTrain\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"notes\":\"Welcome back, James. This first phase is all about rebuilding the habit of running without asking your foot to do too much too soon. Every run is capped at 20 minutes and stays strictly easy — that means the slower end of your easy pace range (5:40–5:58 /km) or slower if your foot gives you any signal. Walk breaks are not a sign of weakness here; they are part of the prescription. Three days per week max: think Tuesday, Thursday, Saturday. Saturday long runs are still capped at 20 minutes in this phase. If you feel any foot discomfort — not just pain, but any unusual tightness or pulling — walk immediately and end the run. The goal of these four weeks is tissue adaptation and confidence, not fitness. Deload in week 4: reduce total volume by 20% and pay close attention to how your foot responds.\",\"includes_deload\":true},{\"phase_type\":\"Base\",\"weeks\":4,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":12,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":18,\"intensity_distribution\":\"90% easy / 10% steady\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"Recovery\",\"CrossTrain\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":342,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":324,\"notes\":\"Your foot has had four weeks of gentle reintroduction. In this phase, we begin to let the Saturday run extend slightly beyond 20 minutes — but only if you have had zero foot symptoms in phase one and only with physiotherapist clearance to progress. Midweek runs stay at or under 20 minutes. We are still not touching speed work of any kind. The slight uptick in pace (toward the faster end of your easy range, 5:24 /km) is permitted on days when you feel genuinely good, but slower is always an option and never a step backward. Deload in week 8: drop back to phase-one volume for one week as a check-in. This is also a good moment to reconnect with your physiotherapist and get a progress assessment before we build further.\",\"includes_deload\":true},{\"phase_type\":\"Build\",\"weeks\":4,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":18,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":26,\"intensity_distribution\":\"80% easy / 20% steady-tempo\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"Tempo\",\"Recovery\",\"CrossTrain\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":336,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":300,\"notes\":\"This is where your pre-injury fitness starts to come back online — and it will come back faster than you might expect, because your aerobic base is still largely intact. Tempo work (at or around 5:00 /km — comfortably hard, not a race effort) is introduced only once per week on Thursdays, and only after physiotherapist clearance for speed work. If clearance has not been given, keep all running easy and simply extend duration. Saturday long runs can now push toward 35–40 minutes depending on how your foot is responding. The 10% weekly volume cap is firm here — plantar fasciitis responds poorly to sudden load spikes. Deload in week 12.\",\"includes_deload\":true},{\"phase_type\":\"Peak\",\"weeks\":2,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":26,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":30,\"intensity_distribution\":\"75% easy / 25% quality\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"Tempo\",\"Interval\",\"Recovery\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":330,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":269,\"notes\":\"Two weeks of your highest training load in this plan. Interval work may be introduced here — short, controlled efforts (200–400m) at interval pace (4:12 /km) — but only with full physiotherapist clearance and only if the previous eight weeks have been symptom-free. Saturday long run can now reach 50–55 minutes. This phase is about testing your rebuilt capacity, not proving anything. If your foot speaks up at any point, we drop back immediately to the Build phase. Your VDOT of 46.5 reflects pre-injury fitness; actual current fitness is likely a VDOT of 42–44, so use these paces as a ceiling, not a floor.\",\"includes_deload\":false},{\"phase_type\":\"Taper\",\"weeks\":2,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":30,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":18,\"intensity_distribution\":\"85% easy / 15% steady\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"Recovery\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":342,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":342,\"notes\":\"The final two weeks are a deliberate wind-down — not because training is over, but because your body needs to consolidate everything it has absorbed. Volume drops significantly; intensity drops with it. This is recovery as investment: the adaptations from the previous 14 weeks are being locked in right now. Keep Saturday runs relaxed and enjoyable. The measure of success for this plan is not a race time or a weekly mileage target — it is arriving at week 16 healthy, consistent, and excited about what comes next.\",\"includes_deload\":false}],\"rationale\":\"James is an intermediate runner with five years of experience and a solid pre-injury VDOT of 46.5 (44:00 10K). However, he is currently managing active plantar fasciitis — a load-sensitive condition that requires a very conservative return-to-running protocol. His physiotherapist has cleared him for 20-minute easy runs only, with no speed work, and walking breaks if any foot pain occurs. His recent training history shows he has already started moving again (6.4 km in the most recent week across 2 runs), which is genuinely encouraging and shows good self-awareness about not rushing back. This 16-week plan is structured in five phases: two Base phases that prioritize tissue adaptation and habit rebuilding before any intensity is introduced, a Build phase where controlled quality work returns (subject to physio clearance), a brief Peak phase to test rebuilt capacity, and a Taper phase to consolidate gains. Volume begins conservatively at 8 km/week — slightly above his most recent week to maintain momentum without spiking load — and builds gradually to a peak of approximately 30 km/week, never exceeding the 10% weekly progression rule. All paces are derived from his pre-injury VDOT of 46.5, with the understanding that current fitness is likely 5–10% lower. Easy pace (5:24–5:58 /km) forms the backbone of the entire plan. Speed work appears only in phases three and four, and only with explicit physiotherapist clearance. Deload weeks occur in weeks 4, 8, and 12. The three-days-per-week structure (recommended: Tuesday, Thursday, Saturday) respects James's stated preference and also provides adequate recovery time between sessions — particularly important for a foot injury where cumulative load is a key risk factor.\",\"warnings\":\"IMPORTANT: This plan is built around your current physiotherapist clearance for 20-minute easy running only. Speed work (Tempo, Interval, Repetition efforts) must NOT be introduced until your physiotherapist explicitly clears you for it — this is non-negotiable for safe plantar fasciitis recovery. If you experience any of the following, stop running immediately and contact your physiotherapist: sharp or stabbing heel/arch pain during or after a run, morning pain that is getting worse week over week rather than better, any new pain in the opposite foot or either knee. Walking breaks are built into the prescription — use them without hesitation whenever your foot asks for them. Do not redistribute missed mileage across other days if you need to skip a session; simply continue from where the plan is. Plantar fasciitis recovery is non-linear — some weeks will feel like regression, and that is normal. Consistency over many weeks matters far more than any single workout.\"}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
